00:38:37.641 --> 00:38:43.080
get this really great honey that's very tasty.
And you also get wax, too. And I make things,

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:46.450
lip balm or candles.

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:52.310
Whittling, I've really got in to making -- this
branch that fell off of a tree, I started

00:38:52.310 --> 00:39:00.850
making spoons and different implements out
of it; carved, carved them.

00:39:00.850 --> 00:39:01.850
OK, I'm almost at the end.

00:39:01.850 --> 00:39:06.260
So kids are -- if you have kids, this kind
of life, kids love it. They have so much fun

00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:14.130
making things. My daughter did some embroidery.
So we had lots of projects, even collecting

00:39:14.130 --> 00:39:19.590
sea glasses, making a DIY activity. Making
their own bread.

00:39:19.590 --> 00:39:26.720
So this is what I learned at the end. Homesteading
happiness in three steps. Make more of your

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:34.780
own stuff. I made a pillow there. They're
just examples of things that we made around

00:39:34.780 --> 00:39:39.820
the house. Make your living- and work-spaces
as personal as possible. These are the people

00:39:39.820 --> 00:39:44.070
that I visited while I wrote the book and
just asked to take pictures of their, their

00:39:44.070 --> 00:39:45.070
workspaces.

00:39:45.070 --> 00:39:50.780
[Pause]

00:39:50.780 --> 00:39:55.580
That guy's a magician, a magic prop maker
in LA.

00:39:55.580 --> 00:39:58.260
[Pause]

00:39:58.260 --> 00:40:01.120
And then, follow Bruce Sterling's guide to
better living. Bruce Sterling is a science

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:05.910
fiction writer and a futurist. And here's
Bruce Sterling's guide. Divide your current

00:40:05.910 --> 00:40:12.200
possessions into four major categories: beautiful
things, emotionally important things, tools,

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:17.880
devices, and appliances that efficiently perform
a useful function, everything else. Enjoy

00:40:17.880 --> 00:40:24.570
using the things in one through three. Get
